### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countSquares(self, matrix: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        if not matrix or not matrix[0]:\n            return 0\n        \n        m, n = len(matrix), len(matrix[0])\n        dp = [[0] * n for _ in range(m)]\n        count = 0\n        \n        for i in range(m):\n            for j in range(n):\n                if matrix[i][j] == 1:\n                    if i == 0 or j == 0:\n                        dp[i][j] = 1\n                    else:\n                        dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1\n                    count += dp[i][j]\n        \n        return count\n```\n\nThis solution uses dynamic programming to count the number of square submatrices with all ones. The `dp` table is used to store the size of the largest square submatrix ending at each cell. The value of `dp[i][j]` is determined by the minimum of the three neighboring cells `dp[i-1][j]`, `dp[i][j-1]`, and `dp[i-1][j-1]`, plus one if the current cell `matrix[i][j]` is 1. The result is the sum of all values in the `dp` table.", "estimated_date": 1575158400000}